name: axios
text:
DEEP DIVE — The gig economy

👇 Let's take a look at the evolving gig economy and the battles between companies and workers. https://t.co/CWIwamae4L

name: axios
text: A victory by gig-economy companies in California to keep classifying their workers as contractors has given the industry a playbook to face rising labor movements nationwide, @imkialikethecar writes. https://t.co/dP5tDqRt8Z

name: axios
text:
California state proposition 22 enshrined their workers as contractors in exchange for limited benefits. 

If Prop 22 had failed, Uber planned to operate only in the Bay Area, LA, Orange County and San Diego, according to communications obtained by Axios. https://t.co/fK69AgoR5w

name: axios
text:
Grocery delivery company Instacart became a critical service for many overnight when cities and states across the U.S. quickly implemented stay-at-home orders to curb the spread of COVID-19. 

The pandemic reportedly brought the company its first profits. https://t.co/HWRYDqap8w

name: axios
text: While the pandemic decimated ride-hailing businesses, delivery companies saw their revenues boosted by the sudden increase in demand from consumers. https://t.co/5AZ0vJOgns https://t.co/ltXiwanQGD

name: axios
text:
Gig workers rode out the deepest economic downturn on record with an imperfect but unprecedented safety net, @courtenay_brown writes. 

It could set the stage for how they could get access to the benefits afforded to other workers in normal times. https://t.co/qxWasYNi5Y

name: axios
text: The rising popularity of the gig economy descriptor — as a catchall for any employees who are "not permanently attached" — is directly related to structural changes in the labor market creating a new way of working, @AjaWMoore writes. https://t.co/zbPWUL2cA6

name: axios
text: There’s a small, but growing number of companies that are attempting to flout the Uber, Lyft and Instacart model and redefine the gig economy, @erica_pandey writes. https://t.co/CZhbhB5Rra

name: axios
text:
Gig companies are hoping a new form of employment will be the key to safeguarding their business models and avoiding a dramatic overhaul — or even collapse — if they’re forced to follow traditional rules. 
https://t.co/4JQaNwaRaO
